            <abstract id="ref101" label="Abstract">Attorney Ryszard Mrotek was born in Lwow, which is in today's Ukraine. He spent the WWII in Warsaw, was arrested during the Warsaw Uprising and send to labor camp in Germany. After liberation he attended high school in Germany, worked as interpreter for the United Nations and moved to the US. He became immigration lawyer and settled in Connecticut. He was very active in local political organizations and served as president of the Polish American Congress, Division of Connecticut. He was also active in other organizations and regularly participated in a theatrical productions of a group called Wiatraki Wyobrazni. This collections consist of records of Polish American Congress as well as some personal records.</abstract>
            <origination label="creator">
                <persname rules="local" source="local">Mrotek, Ryszard</persname>
            </origination>
        </did>
        <bioghist id="ref99">
            <head>Biographical/Historical note</head>
            <p>Atorney Ryszard S. Mrotek was a distinguished and well-renowned attorney in Hartford and New Britain for 25 years before retiring in 1992. His specialty was Immigration and International Law with a Constitutional expertise. Mr. Mrotek was born in Lwow, Poland, he was a messenger for the Polish Home Army during the 1944 Warsaw Uprising. At age 11, he was taken prisoner by German occupational forces and was later liberated by General Patton's troops. He completed high school in Germany and worked there as an interpreter for the United Nations before emigrating to America. He came to the United States as a refugee, settling in Hartford and becoming a naturalized citizen in 1956. Ryszard received his Bachelor of Arts and Juris Doctorate degrees from the University of Connecticut. He served with the 43rd Infantry Division of the Connecticut National Guard for 18 years, as well as active duty in the U.S. Army from 1956 to 1958. Mr. Mrotek was a prominent leader in the Polish community; he was a President of the Polish American Congress, Division of Connecticut and participated in the production of "Wiatraki Wyobrazni'' (a Polish cultural musical); and, for the rapier wit with which he wrote Polish satire. Mr. Mrotek was also active in the Solidarnosc movement, a successful struggle by the people of Poland for freedom from communist oppression. Recognizing that the struggle for freedom in Poland transcended national boundaries and extended to all people, he never ceased to fight for Human and Civil Rights everywhere. Ryszard will be remembered by his peers and clients for his distinguished legal career. He was a member of the American Immigration Lawyers Association and past Chairperson of the AILA CT Chapter.</p>
        </bioghist>
        <prefercite id="ref103">
            <head>Preferred Citation note</head>
            <p>Cite as: Ryszard Mrotek Collection, (CPAA 86-15). Connecticut Polish American Archives, Central Connecticut State University, New Britain.</p>
        </prefercite>
        <scopecontent id="ref100">
            <head>Scope and Contents note</head>
            <p>The collection consists of material related to Mr. Mrotek's presidency in the Polish American Congress, Division of Connecticut.</p>
        </scopecontent>
